## Concept: Docker Image vs Docker Container

| Aspect | Docker Image | Docker Container |
|---|---|---|
| Nature | Static, read-only template | Dynamic, running process |
| Created by | `docker build` or `docker pull` | `docker run` |
| Storage | Registry / local image cache | In-memory + thin writable layer |
| Lifecycle | Persists until explicitly deleted | Lives while its process runs |
| Mutability | Immutable — content-addressed layers | Mutable — changes go to writable layer |
| Analogy | Class / Blueprint / ISO file | Object / Running instance |
| Sharing | One image → many containers | Each container is independent |

**Layer Architecture:**
Docker images are composed of stacked, read-only layers (each `RUN`, `COPY`, `ADD` instruction in a Dockerfile creates a layer). When `docker pull nginx` runs, each layer downloads separately and is cached locally. A container adds one thin **writable layer** on top of the image layers at runtime. Deleting the container removes only that writable layer — the image layers remain intact and reusable.

```
┌─────────────────────────┐  ← Writable container layer (deleted on docker rm)
├─────────────────────────┤
│   nginx config layer    │  ← Read-only image layers
├─────────────────────────┤
│   nginx binary layer    │
├─────────────────────────┤
│   Debian base OS layer  │
└─────────────────────────┘
```

